---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Pagination from '../../../components/Pagination.astro';
import DocCard from '../../../components/DocCard.astro';

const base = '/portfolio';
const previous = 'elevator';
const next = 'hashes';
---

<BaseLayout title="Huffman Compression | ADEN Project" base={base}>
  <Pagination base={base} section="projects/aden" previous={previous} next={next} />

  <section style="max-width:900px; margin:0 auto; padding:2rem 1rem;">
    <h1>Huffman Compression</h1>

    {/* DESCRIPTION */}
    <section id="description" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <h2>Project Description</h2>

      <p>
        Implemented Huffman coding to generate prefix-free variable-length codes
        based on symbol frequency. The system supports full encoding and decoding,
        with validation tests ensuring lossless reconstruction of input data.
      </p>
    </section>

    {/* PHASES */}
    <section id="phases" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <h2>Project Phases</h2>

      <ol>
        <li>Frequency Analysis of Input Text</li>
        <li>Construction of Huffman Tree</li>
        <li>Prefix Code Generation</li>
        <li>Encoding Pipeline Implementation</li>
        <li>Decoding and Validation Testing</li>
        <li>Performance Evaluation</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    {/* ANALYSIS */}
    <section id="analysis" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <h2>Summary of Analysis</h2>

      <p>
        Huffman compression was consistently effective across all files, with performance
        strongly dependent on how closely the weight distribution matched the target text.
      </p>

      <p>
        Across all experiments, compression achieved an average ratio of approximately
        0.614 with a standard deviation of 0.047.
      </p>

      <p>
        Best performance occurred when files were compressed using their own frequency
        distributions, such as “War and Peace” and “Cat in the Hat”.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cross-file compression still performed well overall, suggesting that natural language
        shares broadly similar statistical structure across different texts.
      </p>

      <p>
        If selecting a single universal weighting model, “War and Peace” performed best overall,
        achieving the most consistent compression results (~0.60 average CR).
      </p>

      <DocCard
  title="Huffman Analysis Report"
  iframeId="huffman-analysis"
  pdfHref={`${base}/documents/ADEN_docs/pdf/${encodeURIComponent('Arnav Krishnan - HuffComp - Analysis.pdf')}`}
  htmlHref={`${base}/documents/ADEN_docs/html/Arnav Krishnan - HuffComp - Analysis/ArnavKrishnanHuffCompAnalysis.html`}
  iframeTitle="Huffman Analysis Report"
/>
    </section>

    {/* KEY LEARNINGS */}
    <section id="learnings" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <h2>Key Learnings</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>Compression efficiency depends heavily on symbol frequency distributions.</li>
        <li>Huffman coding converts statistical structure into optimal prefix codes.</li>
        <li>Natural language maintains consistent redundancy patterns across texts.</li>
        <li>Cross-domain frequency models can still generalize effectively.</li>
        <li>Choice of weighting file significantly impacts compression performance.</li>
      </ul>

      <DocCard
        title="Huffman Reflection"
        iframeId="huffman-reflection"
        pdfHref={`${base}/documents/reflections/pdf/${encodeURIComponent('Reflection - HuffmanCompression 1.pdf')}`}
        htmlHref={`${base}/documents/reflections/html/${encodeURIComponent('Reflection - HuffmanCompression 1.html')}`}
        iframeTitle="Huffman Reflection"
      />
    </section>

    {/* NAVIGATION */}
    <section style="margin-top:2rem;">
      <a
        href={`${base}/aden-course`}
        style="color:#0055aa; text-decoration:underline;"
      >
        ← Back to ADEN Course
      </a>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>